strings.CliPreviewModal-Title: Welcome to the GitKraken CLI Preview
strings.CliPreviewModal-BodyContent:
The GitKraken CLI enhances the terminal experience for all things Git by eliminating the need to memorize Git commands and providing powerful visualizations of your repository when you need them.

You have been invited to this limited preview to test what the GitKraken team has been working on and provide feedback that will help us deliver the best CLI experience to all GitKraken users later this year.

Here is what is possible in the preview:

* Open a GitKraken graph when changing into a directory being tracked by Git
  * Toggle the graph panel on/off with `gk graph`
  * Select commits and inspect file diffs
  * Use context-menu options for git operations
  * Complete drag-and-drop actions to merge, rebase, etc.
+ Get autocomplete suggestions while writing Git commands in the terminal
* Use the new `gk` program to interact with the GitKraken GUI from the terminal:
  * `gk graph`- toggles the graph panel on/off
  * Reposition the graph by adding `top` `right` `bottom` or `left` to `gk graph`
  * Additional commands for the `gk` program are currently in development
strings.CliModal-BodyContent:
The GitKraken CLI enhances the terminal experience for all things Git by eliminating the need to memorize Git commands and by providing powerful visualizations of your repository when you need them.

Here is what is possible inside Terminal tabs during the preview:

* Open a GitKraken graph when changing into a directory being tracked by Git
  *  Select commits and inspect file diffs
  *  Use context-menu options for Git operations
  *  Use drag-and-drop actions to merge, rebase, etc.
+ Get autocomplete suggestions while writing Git commands
* Use the new `gk` program to interact with a visualization panel within a Terminal tab. Current commands include:
  *  `gk panel`  - toggle the panel on/off
   *  `top` , `right` , `bottom` , or `left`  will pin the panel to that side of the terminal
  *  `gk graph`  - hide/show the commit graph
  *  `gk diff`  - open the diff view for the current working directory, or the diff between two commits
  *  `gk history`  or `gk blame`  - open the history or blame view for a file
  *  `gk help`  - view the list of commands available
